{
  "doc_id": "50227",
  "text": "While each OCTA method can compensate for bulk tissue motion within a B-scan, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] saccadic eye motion between B-scans could disrupt vessel continuity and reduce the quality of the final angiogram. Different approaches have been explored to address this issue. Because motion in two consecutive scans will be different, registering multiple scans is a potential solution. Orthogonal registration of one xpriority and one y-priority scan has been demonstrated to reduce motion artifacts. [CITATION_5] Alternatively, incorporating eye tracking with the OCTA scan can minimize motion artifacts as well. [CITATION_6] ",
